answers.body_markdown:
The &quot;yet neither overrides the other&quot; part of the error message is required because if one method overrides the other, then the problem of having the same erasure goes away.

The problem of having the same erasure is that the two methods will have the same JVM signature, and the call would be ambiguous. However, if one overrides another, then there is no ambiguity. Which one to call only depends on the runtime type of the instance. Even if you are calling it with `super`, there is also no ambiguity, because the superclass is trivially known.

It is not type-safe for `setAddressList(List&lt;StudentAddress&gt;)` to override `setAddressList(List&lt;Address&gt;)`, so the [overriding rules][1] prohibit this. Think about what you could do if overriding were allowed.

You could do:

```
Person p = new Student();
List&lt;Address&gt; notStudentAddresses = List.of(new Address());
// the setAddressList in Person takes a List&lt;Address&gt;, so this is possible
p.setAddressList(notStudentAddress);
```

What would the code do? Suppose the methods *do* override each other. Then `setAddressList(notStudentAddress)` would call the implementation in `Student`. And that assigns `notStudentAddresses` to the `List&lt;StudentAddress&gt;` field in `Student`. But `notStudentAddresses` is not a `List&lt;StudentAddress&gt;`! We therefore have a problem.

That said, it is also not type-safe in this regard for `setAddressList(List&lt;StudentAddress&gt;)` to override `setAddressList(List)` either, but the overriding rules allow this anyway (by introducing the concept of [*subsignatures*][2], which is a necessary condition for overriding). This is because it is more convenient to use old code written before Java had generics this way.

```
public class SomeVeryOldClass {
    // Suppose this is designed to take a List&lt;String&gt;, but there were no way to say that back then
    public void doThingsWithStrings(List strings) { ... }
}
```
```
public class NewClass extends SomeVeryOldClass {
    // I don&#39;t have to take a raw type List in my overridden method
    // whoever directly using the new class would be type-safe
    @Override
    public void doThingsWithStrings(List&lt;String&gt; strings) { ... }
}
```


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se17/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.4.8.1
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se17/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.4.2

