If _doc_ is _null_ then the _FileNotFoundException_ is being thrown.

You should use a _[File](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/io/File.html)_ object, and check if the file exists using _[File#exists](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/io/File.html#exists())_.  
And, rather than continuing, just exit the method using _return_.

I&#39;m unsure of your requirements, so I attempted to adapt your code.

You can use a _[try-with-resources](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html)_ statement, which will automatically close the _BufferedReader_, which will close _FileReader_, also.  
Not doing so can sometimes create I/O issues.

Additionally, typically when an _IOException_ occurs during a _readLine_ call, you&#39;ll want to exit the loop.  
Although, again, I am unsure of your requirements, so I left it in.

```java
public String leeDoc() {
    File file = new File(&quot;C:/Users/apple/Desktop/FRASES_FOR_HANGMAN.txt&quot;);
    if (!file.exists()) {
        System.out.println(&quot;No se encuentra el fichero&quot;);
        return null;
    }
    String linea = &quot;&quot;;
    try (BufferedReader buff = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file))) {
        while (linea != null) {
            try {
                linea = buff.readLine();
            } catch (IOException e) {
                System.out.println(&quot;No hay frase&quot;);
            }
        }
        return linea;
    } catch (IOException exception) {
        throw new RuntimeException(exception);
    }
}
```

If your file has multiple lines, you can review the following example.

```java
try (BufferedReader buff = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file))) {
    StringBuilder string = new StringBuilder();
    String linea;
    String newline = System.lineSeparator();
    int count = 0;
    while ((linea = buff.readLine()) != null) {
        if (count++ != 0) string.append(newline);
        string.append(linea);
    }
    return string.toString();
}
```

And, if your file only has one line you won&#39;t need the loop.

```java
try (BufferedReader buff = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file))) {
    return buff.readLine();
}
```

